content.text:
ESP32 + DHT makes this easy. Here's the complete sketch — read the sensor, POST to your API every 5 minutes:

```cpp
#include <WiFi.h>
#include <HTTPClient.h>
#include "DHT.h"

// ---- configuration ----
#define DHTPIN  4        // GPIO the DHT data wire is on
#define DHTTYPE DHT22    // change to DHT11 if that's what you have

const char* WIFI_SSID     = "your-wifi";
const char* WIFI_PASSWORD = "your-password";
const char* SERVER_URL    = "http://192.168.1.201:6769/api/v1/sensor/readings";
const char* API_KEY       = "your-api-key";
const char* SENSOR_NAME   = "garage";
const double LATITUDE     = 40.7128;   // your sensor's location
const double LONGITUDE    = -74.0060;
const unsigned long REPORT_INTERVAL_MS = 5UL * 60UL * 1000UL;  // 5 minutes
// -----------------------

DHT dht(DHTPIN, DHTTYPE);

void connectWiFi() {
  if (WiFi.status() == WL_CONNECTED) return;
  Serial.printf("Connecting to %s", WIFI_SSID);
  WiFi.begin(WIFI_SSID, WIFI_PASSWORD);
  while (WiFi.status() != WL_CONNECTED) {
    delay(500);
    Serial.print(".");
  }
  Serial.printf("\nConnected, IP: %s\n", WiFi.localIP().toString().c_str());
}

void sendReading(float tempF, float humidity) {
  char body[192];
  snprintf(body, sizeof(body),
           "{\"sensor_name\":\"%s\",\"latitude\":%.4f,\"longitude\":%.4f,"
           "\"temperature\":%.1f,\"humidity\":%.1f}",
           SENSOR_NAME, LATITUDE, LONGITUDE, tempF, humidity);

  HTTPClient http;
  http.begin(SERVER_URL);
  http.addHeader("Content-Type", "application/json");
  http.addHeader("X-API-Key", API_KEY);
  int status = http.POST(body);
  Serial.printf("POST %s -> %d\n", body, status);
  http.end();
}

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  dht.begin();
  connectWiFi();
}

void loop() {
  connectWiFi();  // reconnects if WiFi dropped

  float humidity = dht.readHumidity();
  float tempF    = dht.readTemperature(true);  // true = Fahrenheit

  if (isnan(humidity) || isnan(tempF)) {
    Serial.println("DHT read failed, will retry next cycle");
  } else {
    sendReading(tempF, humidity);
  }

  delay(REPORT_INTERVAL_MS);
}
```

**Setup steps:**

1. **Libraries** (Arduino IDE → Library Manager): install "DHT sensor library" by Adafruit, which pulls in "Adafruit Unified Sensor". ESP32 board support gives you `WiFi.h`/`HTTPClient.h` for free.
2. **Wiring**: DHT VCC → 3.3V, GND → GND, DATA → GPIO 4 (or any free GPIO — update `DHTPIN`). Add a 10 kΩ pull-up resistor between DATA and VCC unless your sensor is on a breakout board that already has one (most three-pin modules do).
3. **Fahrenheit matters**: `readTemperature(true)` returns °F, which is what your API stores and what the display expects — don't drop that `true`.

**Design choices worth knowing:**

- **It posts to `192.168.1.201:6769` over plain HTTP**, not `https://weather.tallyo.us`. Since the ESP32 sits on the same LAN as the server, going direct is simpler (no TLS certificate handling on the microcontroller) and keeps traffic local. If you later want the sensor to work from elsewhere, switch the URL to the HTTPS one and use `WiFiClientSecure` — happy to show that variant.
- **5-minute interval** pairs well with the server's 1-hour staleness cutoff — you'd need 12 consecutive missed reports before the display falls back to Open-Meteo.
- The `Serial.printf` lines mean you can watch it work in the Serial Monitor (115200 baud): each POST should log `-> 201`. A `401` means wrong API key; `-1` means it couldn't reach the server.

If you tell me whether it's a DHT11 or DHT22 (printed on the plastic housing), the only change is the `DHTTYPE` line — DHT11 also only reports whole degrees and is noticeably less accurate, so don't be alarmed if its numbers look coarse.

